<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-08-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-08-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="26" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d26">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">Hopkins Papers: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The President’s Special Assistant</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Hopkins</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to Prime Minister <persName type="to">Churchill</persName></hi><note n="1" xml:id="d26fn1">Channel of
                                transmission not indicated. This message was sent in reply to
                                Churchill’s telegram of August 10, 1944, <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_16">p. 16</ref>.</note></head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left"><hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi></seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-08-19">August 19, 1944</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Personal and secret to the Prime Minister from Harry L. Hopkins.</p>
                        <p>The President wishes to discuss military requirements for <gloss target="#t_PhaseII1">Phase II</gloss> with you at your next meeting.
                            This means that this matter is in <hi rend="italic">status quo</hi> here
                            for the present.</p>
                        <p>I am looking forward to seeing you and hope you are well.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Harry</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>